## Economy of Indonesia

[Jakarta](/Jakarta), a sprawling metropolis often described as the pulsating heart of the archipelago, serves as Indonesia's undeniable epicenter for [fintech](/Fintech), [financial](/Financial_Centre), and [business services](/Business_services). Within its dynamic urban landscape lies the [Golden Triangle](/Golden_Triangle_of_Jakarta), a testament to the nation's economic ambitions and a hub where capital flows and deals are struck.

The official currency of Indonesia is the [Rupiah](/Indonesian_rupiah) (IDR, Rp), a symbol of the nation's economic sovereignty. The country operates on a standard [fiscal year](/Fiscal_year) that aligns with the [Calendar year](/Calendar_year), running from [1 January to 31 December](/Calendar_year).

Indonesia is an active participant in the global economic arena, engaging with numerous international trade organizations. These include the [Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation](/Asia-Pacific_Economic_Cooperation) (APEC), the [World Trade Organization](/World_Trade_Organization) (WTO), and the [G-20](/G-20_major_economies), a forum for the world's largest economies. It is also a member of the [BRICS](/BRICS) bloc, the [Indian Ocean Rim Association for Regional Cooperation](/Indian_Ocean_Rim_Association_for_Regional_Cooperation) (IOR-ARC), the [Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership](/Regional_Comprehensive_Economic_Partnership) (RCEP), the [ASEAN Free Trade Area](/ASEAN_Free_Trade_Area) (AFTA), and the broader [Association of Southeast Asian Nations](/Association_of_Southeast_Asian_Nations) (ASEAN). Furthermore, Indonesia participates in the [East Asia Summit](/East_Asia_Summit) (EAS) and is a member of the [Asian Development Bank](/Asian_Development_Bank), among others.

Economically, Indonesia is firmly positioned as a [Developing/Emerging](/Developing_country) nation, a status underscored by its classification as a [Newly industrialized country](/Newly_industrialized_country).

### Statistics

As of 2025, Indonesia's population stands at an estimated 284 million people. The nation's economic output, measured by [Gross domestic product](/Gross_domestic_product) (GDP), is projected to reach $1.443 trillion in [nominal](/GDP_(nominal)) terms and $5.015 trillion when adjusted for [Purchasing power parity](/Purchasing_power_parity) (PPP). These figures place Indonesia as the [17th largest economy in the world by nominal GDP](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)) and the [7th largest in terms of GDP (PPP)](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)).

The economy has demonstrated resilience and growth, with a projected GDP growth rate of 5.0% in 2024, followed by 4.9% in 2025, and anticipated growth of 4.7% in 2026 and 4.9% in 2027. This sustained growth translates to a GDP per capita of $5,074 (nominal) and $17,634 (PPP) in 2025. Consequently, its GDP per capita ranks [121th (nominal)](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_per_capita_(nominal)) and [104th (PPP)](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_per_capita_(PPP)) globally.

The Indonesian economy is diversified across its key sectors: [Agriculture](/Primary_sector_of_the_economy) contributes 13.7%, [Industry](/Secondary_sector_of_the_economy) accounts for 41%, and the [Services](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy) sector makes up 45.4% of the GDP, based on 2017 estimates.

[Inflation](/Inflation), as measured by the [Consumer price index](/Consumer_price_index) (CPI), was recorded at 2.86% in October 2025. The nation is making strides in poverty reduction, with 1.6% of the population living in [multidimensional poverty](/Multidimensional_Poverty_Index) as of 2024. A national poverty line indicates 8.57% of the population below the poverty line in September 2024, with 68% living on less than $8.30 per day in 2024. The [Gini coefficient](/Gini_coefficient), a measure of income inequality, stands at a medium 34.9 in 2024.

Indonesia's [Human Development Index](/Human_Development_Index) (HDI) is 0.728, classifying it as "high" and ranking it 113th globally in 2023. The [Inequality-adjusted HDI](/List_of_countries_by_inequality-adjusted_HDI) is 0.608, placing it 86th. The [Corruption Perceptions Index](/Corruption_Perceptions_Index) rated Indonesia at 37 out of 100 points in 2024, ranking it 99th.

The labor force comprised 147.8 million individuals in 2023, with an employment rate of 75%. The occupational distribution shows 27.7% in [Agriculture](/Primary_sector_of_the_economy), 22.6% in [Industry](/Secondary_sector_of_the_economy), and 49.6% in [Services](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy) as of 2020. The unemployment rate was 4.82% in 2024.

Indonesia's industrial landscape is broad and dynamic, encompassing key sectors such as [palm oil](/Palm_oil), [coal](/Coal), [petroleum](/Petroleum_industry), [petrochemicals](/Petrochemicals), and [liquefied natural gas](/Liquefied_natural_gas). It also has significant [vehicle](/Automotive_industry), [electronics](/Electronics_industry), and [transportation](/Material-handling_equipment) industries, alongside machinery, steel, and telecommunications. The electric power, food processing, wood, textile, footwear, and consumer goods sectors are also vital. Furthermore, the pulp and paper, handicrafts, chemicals, rubber, pharmaceuticals, financial services, and seafood industries contribute significantly, as does the [smelting](/Smelting) and [tourism](/Tourism_industry) sectors.

In 2023, Indonesia's exports reached $298.2 billion, with key goods including [palm oil](/Palm_oil), [steel](/Steel), metals, machinery and industrial equipment, chemicals, liquefied natural gas, textiles, footwear, automobiles, transportation products, wooden products, and plastics. Its main export partners are [China](/China) (24.2%), [ASEAN](/ASEAN) (18.2%), the [United States](/United_States) (10.6%), [India](/India) (8.2%), and [Japan](/Japan) (7.5%).

Imports in 2023 totaled $268.3 billion, with major categories including machinery and industrial equipment, steel, foodstuffs, petroleum products, electronics, raw materials, chemicals, and transportation products. Key import partners include [China](/China) (36.3%), [ASEAN](/ASEAN) (17.5%), [Japan](/Japan) (7.5%), and the [European Union](/European_Union) (6.4%).

The stock of [Foreign direct investment](/Foreign_direct_investment) (FDI) was $262.92 billion inward and $103.94 billion outward in 2023. The [Current account](/Current_account_(balance_of_payments)) showed a surplus of +$3.46 billion in 2021. Gross [external debt](/External_debt) stood at $396.3 billion in Q2 2023.

Public finances in 2025 estimate government debt at 38.6% of GDP. [Foreign reserves](/Foreign_exchange_reserves) were $156.1 billion in January 2025. The [Budget balance](/Government_budget_balance) was projected at -1.49% of GDP for 2025, with revenues estimated at $182.1 billion and expenses at $216.1 billion for 2024.

Indonesia holds a stable credit rating from major agencies. [Japan Credit Rating Agency](/Japan_Credit_Rating_Agency) rates it A- (Domestic Currency) and BBB+ (Foreign Currency and Bond), with a stable outlook. [Standard & Poor's](/Standard_%26_Poor%27s) assigns BBB (Domestic and Foreign) with a stable outlook. [Moody's](/Moody%27s) rates it Baa2 with a stable outlook, and [Fitch](/Fitch_Group) gives it BBB (Local Currency, Foreign Currency, and Country Ceiling) with a stable outlook. All monetary values are in [US dollars](/United_States_dollar) unless otherwise specified.

### History

Indonesia's economic journey is a complex tapestry woven through periods of colonial rule, revolutionary struggle, and ambitious nation-building.

#### Sukarno Era

In the nascent years following the [proclamation of Indonesian independence](/Proclamation_of_Indonesian_independence), the nation was left in economic ruins by the [Japanese occupation](/Japanese_occupation_of_the_Dutch_East_Indies) and the subsequent [Indonesian National Revolution](/Indonesian_National_Revolution). Commodity exports, like rubber and oil, plummeted to mere fractions of their pre-war levels, signaling the immense task of rebuilding. The establishment of the Indonesian State Bank ( [Bank Negara Indonesia](/Bank_Negara_Indonesia) , BNI) in July 1946 marked a crucial step towards financial independence, tasked with issuing the nation's first currency, the ORI (Oeang Republik Indonesia), a precursor to the [Rupiah](/Indonesian_rupiah). However, the proliferation of various currencies and the ease of counterfeiting the ORI only exacerbated economic instability.

The period between 1949 and 1960 was fraught with economic turbulence. Despite the Netherlands formally recognizing Indonesia's independence through the [Dutch-Indonesian Round Table Conference](/Dutch-Indonesian_Round_Table_Conference), the dissolution of the [United States of Indonesia](/United_States_of_Indonesia) in 1950, the ensuing [liberal democracy period](/Liberal_democracy_period_in_Indonesia), the nationalization of De Javasche Bank into [Bank Indonesia](/Bank_Indonesia), and the seizure of Dutch corporate assets following the [West New Guinea dispute](/West_New_Guinea_dispute) all contributed to the devaluation of currency and economic uncertainty.

The [guided democracy era](/Guided_Democracy_in_Indonesia) under Sukarno in the 1960s witnessed a drastic economic decline. Political instability, coupled with inexperience in macroeconomic management, led to widespread poverty and hunger. By the time Sukarno was ousted in the mid-1960s, the economy was in shambles, characterized by hyperinflation nearing 1,000% annually, dwindling export revenues, crumbling infrastructure, factories operating at a mere fraction of their capacity, and negligible investment. Yet, it's worth noting that the subsequent economic recovery in the post-1960 era was considered remarkable, especially given the limited formal education opportunities for indigenous Indonesians under Dutch colonial policies.

#### New Order

The advent of the New Order administration, led by President Suharto, ushered in a period of economic discipline. Inflation was brought under control, the currency stabilized, foreign debt was rescheduled, and foreign aid and investment began to flow in, notably through the [Inter-Governmental Group on Indonesia](/Inter-Governmental_Group_on_Indonesia) and the influence of the [Berkeley Mafia](/Berkeley_Mafia). For many years, Indonesia was the sole Southeast Asian member of [OPEC](/Organization_of_Petroleum_Exporting_Countries). The oil price surge in the 1970s provided a substantial export revenue windfall, fueling sustained economic growth averaging over 7% annually from 1968 to 1981.

However, this reliance on state regulation and fluctuating oil prices led to a slowdown, with growth averaging 4.5% per annum between 1981 and 1988. A series of economic reforms in the late 1980s, including a managed devaluation of the rupiah to boost export competitiveness and deregulation of the financial sector, reignited growth. Foreign investment poured into Indonesia, particularly into the burgeoning export-oriented manufacturing sector, leading to an average economic growth of over 7% from 1989 to 1997. This period saw a remarkable 545% increase in GDP per capita between 1970 and 1980, driven by the oil export boom. Yet, beneath this veneer of growth lay structural weaknesses: weak and corrupt institutions, significant public debt due to financial sector mismanagement, rapid depletion of natural resources, and a pervasive culture of patronage and corruption.

Corruption reached alarming levels in the 1990s, permeating the highest echelons of power, with Suharto himself often cited as a prime example of a corrupt leader by [Transparency International](/Transparency_International). This environment fostered a weak legal system, hindering contract enforcement, debt collection, and bankruptcy proceedings. Banking practices were rudimentary, heavily reliant on collateral, and marked by frequent violations of prudential regulations. Economic distortions were prevalent, stemming from non-tariff barriers, rent-seeking by state-owned enterprises, domestic subsidies, and trade restrictions.

The [1997 Asian financial crisis](/1997_Asian_financial_crisis) struck Indonesia with devastating force, triggering a profound economic and political crisis. The initial government response, including floating the rupiah, raising interest rates, and tightening fiscal policy, proved insufficient. An agreement with the [International Monetary Fund](/International_Monetary_Fund) (IMF) in October 1997 aimed at macroeconomic stabilization and policy reform, targeting problematic policies like the National Car Program and the [clove](/Clove) monopoly, which disproportionately benefited Suharto's family. Despite these efforts, the rupiah's continued weakness, coupled with widespread riots, forced Suharto's resignation in May 1998. President [B. J. Habibie](/B._J._Habibie) subsequently signed an Extended Fund Facility (EFF) with the IMF in August 1998, incorporating significant structural reform targets. President [Abdurrahman Wahid](/Abdurrahman_Wahid) continued these efforts, signing another EFF in January 2000.

The crisis exacted a severe toll. By November 1997, public debt had soared to $60 billion due to currency depreciation. In 1998, real GDP contracted by a staggering 13.1%, with the economy hitting its nadir in mid-1999 with a mere 0.8% growth. Inflation skyrocketed to 72% in 1998, though it later subsided to 2% in 1999. The rupiah's value plummeted from around Rp 2,600 per US dollar in August 1997 to Rp 11,000 by January 1998, and even higher in subsequent months. While it recovered to the Rp 8,000–10,000 range, it began a gradual depreciation again, exceeding Rp 11,000 by 2013 and reaching around Rp 13,000 by late 2016.

#### Reform Era

Since the introduction of an inflation target in 2000, the GDP deflator and [CPI](/Consumer_price_index) have shown more moderate growth compared to the pre-crisis decades, though inflation did experience temporary spikes due to government policy shifts, such as changes in fiscal subsidies in 2005 and 2008.

