In late 2004, Indonesia experienced a brief 'mini-crisis' triggered by rising [international oil prices](/World_oil_market_chronology_from_2003), causing the currency to reach Rp 12,000 per US dollar before stabilizing. Under President [Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono](/Susilo_Bambang_Yudhoyono), the government was compelled to reduce substantial fuel subsidies, which were projected to cost $14 billion in October 2005.

By February 2007, the unemployment rate stood at 9.75%. Despite a global economic slowdown, Indonesia's economic growth reached a ten-year high of 6.3% in 2007, sufficient to reduce poverty and lower unemployment to 8.46% by February 2008. Unlike its export-reliant neighbors, Indonesia navigated the global recession relatively well, bolstered by strong domestic demand and a fiscal stimulus package equivalent to about 1.4% of GDP. It ranked as the third-fastest growing economy in the G20, after India and China. The IMF revised its 2009 forecast for Indonesia upwards to 3–4%. This resilience was attributed to strong fundamentals and wide-ranging economic and financial reforms, including debt reduction and strengthened banking sector capitalization.

In 2012, Indonesia's real GDP growth was 6%, a rate that gradually declined to below 5% by 2015. Following President Joko Widodo's ascent to power, the government introduced measures to streamline regulations for foreign direct investments. Indonesia managed to maintain GDP growth slightly above 5% in 2016–2017, though challenges persisted with currency weakening, declining exports, and stagnating consumer spending. The unemployment rate in 2019 was 5.3%.

The [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic) presented significant challenges between 2019 and 2020, leading to a 2.1% contraction in GDP in 2020—the first annual decline in over two decades. This was largely due to [large-scale social restrictions (PSBB)](/Indonesia_large-scale_social_restrictions) that disrupted economic activities. Nevertheless, government stimulus and social assistance programs provided a buffer. By the third quarter of 2020, economic contraction slowed, signaling nascent recovery.

Indonesia's economy rebounded in 2021 with a 4.4% growth rate, supported by domestic demand and global economic improvements. Growth accelerated to 5.0% in 2022, further boosted by reduced uncertainty and successful vaccination efforts.

In October 2024, [Prabowo Subianto](/Prabowo_Subianto) assumed the presidency, inheriting an economy with steady growth but facing structural hurdles. His administration unveiled ambitious plans, including a large-scale free school meals program and a commitment to transition away from fossil fuel power plants. To fund these initiatives, significant budget cuts were implemented, impacting various sectors and raising concerns about public services. The persistent presence of criminal networks, known as [preman](/Preman_(Indonesian_gangster)), and certain mass organizations (ormas) continue to pose challenges to foreign investment and economic development, particularly in industrial zones, leading to substantial financial losses and deterring investors.

The [Indonesian rupiah](/Indonesian_rupiah) (IDR) experienced significant volatility between 2019 and 2025. The COVID-19 pandemic saw a sharp depreciation, reaching around Rp 16,500 per US dollar in 2020. By 2021-2022, the currency stabilized, but renewed pressure emerged in 2023-2024 due to political uncertainties and fiscal policy concerns, depreciating to around Rp 16,200 per dollar by April 2024. In early 2025, the rupiah hit a five-year low, prompting intervention from [Bank Indonesia](/Bank_Indonesia). The central bank maintained its benchmark interest rate at 5.75% in March to support the rupiah, later cutting it to 5.50% in May as the currency showed signs of stabilization.

