#### Sectors

##### Agriculture

[Agriculture](/Agriculture_in_Indonesia) remains a cornerstone of the Indonesian economy, contributing approximately 14.43% to GDP. A significant portion of the population, around 49 million people (41% of the workforce), is employed in this sector, utilizing about 30% of the nation's land area. Key agricultural commodities include rice, cassava, peanuts, [natural rubber](/Natural_rubber), cocoa, coffee, [palm oil](/Palm_oil), and copra. Poultry, beef, pork, and eggs are also important products. Indonesia's dominance in [palm oil](/Palm_oil) production is globally recognized, as it is the world's largest producer and consumer, supplying roughly half of the global demand. Plantations cover vast areas, with ongoing plans for expansion to boost productivity, although concerns regarding the [social and environmental impacts of palm oil](/Social_and_environmental_impact_of_palm_oil) production persist.

##### Seafood

Indonesia's [seafood](/Seafood) industry is robust, with a total production of approximately 22.31 million metric tons in 2015, valued at around $18.10 billion. While the trend in wild fish capture remained steady, there was a notable increase in [aquaculture](/Aquaculture) production during the 2011–2015 period. Indonesia ranks as the second most productive country globally in seafood production, following China.

##### Palm Oil

The [palm oil](/Palm_oil) industry is a critical pillar of Indonesia's economy. As the world's leading producer and consumer, Indonesia accounts for about half of the global supply. In 2016, the country produced over 34.6 million metric tons, exporting 25.1 million tons. This sector contributes significantly to GDP and provides employment for millions. In response to environmental and human rights critiques, efforts are underway to promote [sustainability](/Sustainability) within the industry, guided by principles set by the [Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil](/Roundtable_on_Sustainable_Palm_Oil) (RSPO).

##### Coconut

Indonesia is the world's largest producer of [coconut](/Coconut), yielding approximately 18.5 million tons annually. The coconut holds deep cultural and symbolic significance in Indonesian mythology and traditions, often referred to as the "Tree of Life" for its perceived fertility and life-sustaining attributes.

#### Industry

##### Oil and Mining

Indonesia was once the sole Southeast Asian member of the [Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries](/Organization_of_Petroleum_Exporting_Countries) (OPEC), though it suspended its membership in 2009. Despite substantial petroleum production, the country remains a net oil importer. Oil and gas extraction, refining, and related sectors have historically contributed significantly to GDP. However, a decline in crude oil and condensate output, attributed to aging fields and underinvestment, coupled with rising domestic consumption, has led to increased oil imports. The state retains ownership of all petroleum and mineral rights, with foreign firms operating under production-sharing agreements. Fuel prices have historically been subsidized, but significant reductions in these subsidies have been implemented to manage the budget deficit and redirect funds towards development.

Indonesia is a major global player in mineral production, particularly in tin, copper, nickel, gold, and coal. It is the world's largest producer of nickel and a significant producer of cobalt. The [Grasberg mine](/Grasberg_mine) in Papua is one of the world's largest gold and copper reserves. Coal production is substantial, making Indonesia a top global producer, with a Domestic Market Obligation (DMO) regulation ensuring sufficient supply for domestic needs. Efforts are also underway to develop [upgraded brown coal](/Coal_upgrading_technology) to enhance its export value. Various international mining companies have substantial investments in Indonesia.

The [Joko Widodo](/Joko_Widodo) administration continued the policy of [resource nationalism](/Resource_nationalism), nationalizing assets previously held by multinational corporations. Policies were implemented to prioritize domestic crude oil sales to state-owned [Pertamina](/Pertamina) to reduce imports.

##### Renewable Energy

Despite possessing significant potential for renewable energy development, Indonesia continues to rely heavily on fossil fuels for electricity production. This reliance risks creating [stranded assets](/Stranded_assets) and missing out on renewable energy investments. The national electricity company, [PLN](/Perusahaan_Listrik_Negara), is often cited as an impediment to renewable energy expansion, though the exact source of resistance remains complex, involving various government bodies and external actors.

##### Construction

The construction sector plays a vital role in Indonesia's economic development, contributing significantly to GDP. The industry's expansion is fueled by major capital expenditure projects, including ambitious government initiatives and public-private partnerships for infrastructure development, such as high-speed rail, mass rapid transit systems, toll roads, and the new capital city, [Nusantara (city)](/Nusantara_(city)).

##### Manufacturing

Indonesia's [manufacturing](/Manufacturing) sector is a key driver of its economic growth, aiming to propel the nation into the top ten global economies by 2030. Major production areas include textiles, garments, food and beverages, electronics, automotive, and chemicals, with a substantial number of micro, small, and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs) dominating the landscape. The sector has shown consistent growth and attracted significant investment. Indonesia has emerged as a major manufacturing nation, surpassing the manufacturing sectors of several developed countries in scale. The industry sector, including manufacturing, employs a considerable portion of the workforce.

The sector faces challenges such as intense international competition, rising labor costs, high logistics expenses, difficulties in accessing credit, and regulatory inconsistencies. However, its growing middle class and competitive workforce continue to attract foreign investors.

###### Automotive Industry

Indonesia is a significant market for both motorcycles and cars. The domestic production of motorcycles is largely self-sufficient with a high ratio of local components. Leading global brands dominate the car market, with local manufacturers also introducing [Indonesian national cars](/Indonesian_car) and contributing to exports. The automotive sector is projected to become a major export contributor. Indonesian automotive companies are increasingly capable of producing vehicles with a high percentage of local content.

###### Defense

Indonesia's defense industry is driven by a strategic imperative for self-reliance, stemming from past arms embargoes, and a desire for economic value creation through job creation and technology transfer. Key state-owned enterprises like [PT Pindad](/Pindad), [PT PAL](/PAL_Indonesia), and [PT DI](/Indonesian_Aerospace) specialize in areas ranging from weapons systems and naval shipbuilding to aerospace. Indonesia is also pursuing domestic production of advanced military equipment through collaborations with international partners, aiming to bolster its defense capabilities and industrial base.

#### Services

##### Finance, Real Estate, and Business Services

Indonesia's financial sector is substantial, supporting a vast network of small businesses, many of which are embracing online platforms. Google's presence signifies the growing importance of the digital economy. State assets are significant, and financial services are concentrated among domestic and foreign conglomerates.

##### Others

The textile sector anticipates considerable investment, with exports contributing substantially to the national economy. Indonesia also plays a significant role in the global labor market, with millions of its citizens working overseas and sending back substantial remittances, making it one of the top remittance-receiving countries globally.

#### Regional Economies

Indonesia's economy is characterized by significant regional disparities. The GDP distribution across its 34 provinces highlights the economic concentration in major islands like Java and Sumatra, with [Jakarta](/Jakarta) leading as the economic powerhouse. Other provinces like East Java, West Java, Central Java, North Sumatra, and Riau are also major contributors.

#### Foreign Economic Relations

##### Trade Statistics

Indonesia maintains a robust trade balance, with goods exports consistently exceeding imports. Key export commodities include agricultural products, minerals, and manufactured goods, with major destinations being [China](/China), [ASEAN](/ASEAN), the [United States](/United_States), and [India](/India). Imports primarily consist of machinery, industrial equipment, raw materials, and consumer goods, with [China](/China) and [ASEAN](/ASEAN) being the largest sources.

##### ASEAN

Intra-[ASEAN](/ASEAN) trade has been growing, though exports to non-ASEAN countries remain significant. The [ASEAN Framework Agreement on Trade in Services](/ASEAN_Framework_Agreement_on_Trade_in_Services) (AFAS) aims to liberalize trade in services, with several packages of commitments already concluded. Mutual Recognition Agreements (MRAs) facilitate the movement of professionals across member states. Efforts are also underway to integrate stock exchanges and establish a [ASEAN Single Aviation Market](/ASEAN_Single_Aviation_Market) to foster a unified aviation sector.

##### Japan

The [Indonesia–Japan Economic Partnership Agreement](/Indonesia%E2%80%93Japan_Economic_Partnership_Agreement) (IJEPA) facilitates trade, investment, and the flow of people between the two nations. Japan is a major investor in Indonesia, particularly in the automotive, electronics, energy, and mining sectors. Indonesia is a key supplier of natural resources to Japan, while Indonesia remains a significant market for Japanese goods.

##### China

Trade relations with [China](/China) have intensified significantly, making it Indonesia's largest export destination and a primary source of imports. While this has boosted bilateral trade, it has also raised concerns about the impact of cheap Chinese products on domestic industries, prompting calls for renegotiation of trade terms. China's economic rise has increased its influence within the [bamboo network](/Bamboo_network) of overseas Chinese businesses in Southeast Asia.

##### South Korea

Bilateral trade and investment between Indonesia and South Korea have expanded considerably. South Korea is a major foreign investor, with numerous companies operating in various sectors. A comprehensive economic partnership agreement, akin to a free trade agreement, has been signed to further deepen economic cooperation and reduce tariffs on products exchanged between the two nations.

##### United States

Trade relations with the [United States](/United_States) have historically been significant, with substantial exports and imports. The US has been a key investor, particularly in the oil and gas and mining sectors. Indonesia's trade status with the US has been subject to review, impacting trade preferences.

##### European Union

The [European Union](/European_Union) and Indonesia maintain strong commercial ties, with bilateral trade showing an upward trend. Indonesia primarily exports agricultural products and processed resources to the EU, while importing machinery, chemicals, and manufactured goods. The EU is a significant investor in Indonesia. Negotiations are ongoing for a Comprehensive Economic Partnership Agreement to enhance trade, investment, and services.

##### India

Indonesia and [India](/India) have set ambitious targets to increase bilateral trade and investment. Economic ties are further strengthened through India's free trade agreement with ASEAN.

#### Free Trade Efforts

Indonesia is actively engaged in pursuing various international trade agreements to promote economic growth and integration. These include bilateral agreements with countries like [Australia](/Australia), [Canada](/Canada), [Chile](/Chile), [EFTA](/European_Free_Trade_Association), [EAEU](/Eurasian_Economic_Union), [EU](/European_Union), [Iran](/Iran), [Japan](/Japan), [Mozambique](/Mozambique), [Pakistan](/Pakistan), [Palestine](/Palestine), [Peru](/Peru), [South Korea](/South_Korea), and the [United Arab Emirates](/United_Arab_Emirates). Furthermore, Indonesia participates in multilateral trade frameworks such as the [ASEAN Free Trade Area](/ASEAN_Free_Trade_Area) (AFTA), the [ASEAN–China Free Trade Area](/ASEAN%E2%80%93China_Free_Trade_Area) (ACFTA), the [ASEAN–India Free Trade Area](/ASEAN%E2%80%93India_Free_Trade_Area) (AIFTA), the [ASEAN–Japan Comprehensive Economic Partnership](/ASEAN_Free_Trade_Area) (AJCEP), the [ASEAN–Korea Free Trade Area](/ASEAN_Free_Trade_Area) (AKFTA), the [ASEAN–Australia–New Zealand Free Trade Area](/ASEAN_Free_Trade_Area) (AANZFTA), and the [Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership](/Regional_Comprehensive_Economic_Partnership) (RCEP). Trade facilitation efforts are also ongoing with organizations like the [Developing Eight Countries](/Developing_8_Countries) (D-8).

